[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1954[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Patient: yes please
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1955[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1956[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Bot:     [Surfaces safety plan steps from patient's
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1957[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          on-file plan, formatted clearly with the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1958[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          specific contacts and steps]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1959[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1960[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          Stay with me. Priya is joining now.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1961[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1962[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Priya, licensed counselor, joins the chat with
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1963[0m:[38;5;10m[49m  conversation context already loaded]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1964[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1965[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Priya:   Hi Sam, this is Priya. I'm a licensed
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1966[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          counselor with the platform. I've read what
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1967[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          you and the support tool have been talking
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1968[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          about. You did the right thing reaching out.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1969[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          Tell me a little more about what's been
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1970[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          happening tonight.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1971[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1972[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1973[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks (illustrative, your mileage varies):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1974[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1975[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Pre-bot baseline (existing care alone) | Post-bot (engaged members) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1976[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------------------------------|----------------------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1977[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Crisis-screening sensitivity (in test corpus) | N/A | Target 95%+ as launch-gate |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1978[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Crisis-screening false-negative rate | N/A | Target less than 2% as launch-gate |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1979[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Warm-handoff completion rate | N/A | Target 70-85% (patient accepts handoff when offered) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1980[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Time-to-first-counselor-response after handoff | Variable, often minutes-to-hours | Target under 60 seconds for acute, under 5 minutes for sub-acute |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1981[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Engagement attrition by 6 months | N/A | 35-55% (the central operational risk) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1982[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Companion-pattern-violation rate | N/A | Target near zero, monitored by sampled review |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1983[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | PHQ-9 trajectory in engaged members | Typical baseline | Modest improvement averaged across cohort, with substantial individual variation |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1984[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | GAD-7 trajectory in engaged members | Typical baseline | Modest improvement averaged across cohort |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1985[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Patient satisfaction (CSAT) | N/A | Generally positive, varies by program design |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1986[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-active-member infrastructure cost | N/A | $5-12 per member per month |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1987[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-active-member total cost (including licensed-clinician workforce) | N/A | $20-80 per member per month |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1988[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Citation-coverage rate | N/A | 95%+ as launch-gate target |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1989[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-cohort outcome disparity | Often invisible | Monitored explicitly |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1990[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1991[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO: replace illustrative figures with measured results from the deployment. The ranges above are typical for evidence-based digital mental-health support deployments but vary substantially with program design, target population, and engagement intensity. Published evidence for hybrid AI-plus-human mental-health programs includes peer-reviewed studies of programs from Lyra, Spring Health, Talkspace, Headspace Health, Wysa, Woebot, and others, with effect sizes varying. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1992[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1993[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1994[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1995[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Engagement attrition.** The central operational risk. Mental-health-specific drivers compound this (depressive symptoms reduce engagement capacity; anxiety about disclosures; difficulty returning after disclosure-heavy sessions). Mitigation: relationship-quality engineering with mental-health expertise; gentle re-engagement after difficult sessions; per-cohort attrition monitoring.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1996[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Crisis-screen calibration.** False-negatives are life-or-death. False-positives erode trust if too frequent. The calibration is the most important clinical-quality decision in the deployment. Mitigation: validated instrument language, sampled review with licensed mental-health clinicians, false-negative rate as launch-gate metric, per-cohort calibration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1997[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Companion-pattern drift.** Even careful bots drift in extended interactions. Mitigation: explicit prompt constraints, output safety detection, sampled review with companion-pattern as a tagged failure mode, recurring disclosure refresh, conversation-style review by behavioral-health clinicians.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1998[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Reaching the patients who need it most.** The patients with greatest unmet mental-health need are often the patients with the least access to and comfort with digital tools. Mitigation: multi-channel deployment, language and cultural-fit investment, per-cohort outreach, integration with care-management and care-navigation pathways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1999[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Cultural and linguistic gaps in mental-health framing.** Mental-health content developed in one cultural framework often does not translate to others. Mitigation: per-language and per-cultural-context content development with behavioral-health-clinical-leadership review; per-cohort outcome monitoring; explicit recognition of stigma and help-seeking variations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2000[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Comorbidity complexity.** Patients with comorbid substance-use disorders, eating disorders, primary psychotic-spectrum diagnoses, or cognitive impairment may be outside the bot's scope. Mitigation: explicit population-eligibility criteria; eligibility-check at enrollment; off-ramp to specialized care for excluded populations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2001[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Mandatory-reporting handling.** Disclosures requiring statutory reporting are state-specific and category-specific. Mitigation: routing to a licensed mandatory reporter with conversation context; institutional policy reviewed by legal counsel; state-specific variations encoded.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2002[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Privacy concerns and surveillance flavor.** Mental-health bots can feel surveillance-flavored, especially with bot-initiated check-ins. Mitigation: defaulting to patient-initiated engagement; explicit opt-in for check-ins; engagement-fatigue monitoring; clear privacy framing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2003[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Outcome-attribution challenges.** Engaged patients are not a random sample, and mental-health outcomes have many confounders. Mitigation: matched-cohort or quasi-experimental analysis; recognition that observational correlation is suggestive, not causal; long-time-horizon commitment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2004[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Long-term-relationship maintenance.** Over years, patients' mental-health needs change; the bot's content and engagement style may need to evolve. Mitigation: clinical-leadership-reviewed content updates; periodic patient-feedback solicitation; clear off-boarding pathway when bot is no longer the right level of support.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2005[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Regulatory positioning shifts.** FDA guidance on digital mental-health is evolving. Mitigation: regulatory-strategy artifact reviewed regularly; architectural flexibility for either non-regulated or registered SaMD positioning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2006[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Care-team integration ambiguity.** The bot may operate parallel to the patient's existing therapist or psychiatrist, which raises coordination questions. Mitigation: explicit consent posture for care-team sharing; structured summary delivery only with consent; clear bot scope clarifying what the bot is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2007[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Adversarial inputs.** Patients (or bad actors) attempting to extract information, bypass crisis screening, or test the system. Mitigation: input-safety pipeline with prompt-injection detection; output-safety pipeline; per-language adversarial test corpus.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2008[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **AI-companion-product reputational drift.** The broader category includes companion products that have caused harm; institutions deploying support bots must distinguish themselves through architecture, scope, and governance, not just messaging.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2009[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Liability exposure for missed crises.** A bot that fails a crisis screen and a patient is subsequently harmed is a foreseeable liability exposure. Mitigation: false-negative-rate launch-gate; warm-handoff capacity sized appropriately; institutional malpractice carrier involvement; documented FDA-strategy artifact.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2010[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Equity disparities in engagement and outcomes.** Per-cohort monitoring may reveal that the bot reaches and benefits some populations more than others. Mitigation: per-cohort monitoring as launch-gate; periodic clinical-quality review with explicit equity focus; targeted outreach and content adaptation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2011[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2012[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2013[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2014[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Why This Isn't Production-Ready
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2015[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2016[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pseudocode and architecture above demonstrate the pattern. A production deployment needs to close several gaps that are intentionally out of scope for a recipe.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2017[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2018[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Therapeutic-content-corpus governance with full behavioral-health-clinical-leadership signoff.** The single largest pre-deployment investment is curating, validating, and signing off on the therapeutic-content library. CBT modules, behavioral-activation exercises, mindfulness practices, distress-tolerance skills, journaling prompts, sleep-hygiene content, and condition-specific psychoeducation each have defined indications and contraindications. The library is owned by behavioral-health clinical leadership. Each piece has an effective date and an annual review schedule.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2019[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2020[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Crisis-screening-classifier validation.** The crisis classifier is validated against a held-out corpus of crisis-presentation cases curated by clinical leadership before launch and on each material update. False-negative rate is the launch-gate metric. Per-cohort calibration accounts for linguistic and cultural variations in crisis expression.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2021[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2022[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Warm-handoff workforce sized appropriately.** The licensed-clinician workforce (employed or contracted) is sized to the patient population and the expected handoff volume, with peak-hour capacity for evening and overnight surges. Under-sized capacity is a safety gap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2023[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2024[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Mental-health-specific privacy and consent posture with state-specific variations.** Some states (notably California, New York, Illinois, Massachusetts, and others) have enhanced mental-health-record privacy protections that exceed HIPAA baseline. The consent and data-handling posture is reviewed by counsel familiar with state-specific statutes. <!-- TODO: verify; mental-health-privacy state law variations are documented in legal guides; specific provisions vary by state and continue to evolve -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2025[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2026[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Mandatory-reporting routing with state-specific variations.** Mandatory-reporting categories (child abuse, elder abuse, intimate-partner violence, certain mental-health crisis types) and reporting requirements vary by state. The institution's mandatory-reporting policy is reviewed by legal counsel and operationalized for each state in which patients reside.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2027[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2028[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA-strategy artifact with regulatory-counsel review.** The institutional regulatory positioning is documented, reviewed by FDA-experienced regulatory counsel, and maintained as the deployment evolves.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2029[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2030[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Companion-pattern avoidance discipline.** The system prompt, the output safety, the persona-and-tone evaluator, the conversation review process, and the institutional content-policy all enforce companion-pattern avoidance. Sampled review specifically tags companion-pattern-violations as a failure mode.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2031[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2032[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Citation-grounding discipline as architectural floor.** Every therapeutic-content delivery is grounded in cited library content with version preserved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2033[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2034[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team integration with workflow design and consent enforcement.** The therapist, psychiatrist, or PCP receives consent-gated summaries through their workflow tooling. The integration is designed for the care team's workflow, not as a parallel data stream.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2035[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2036[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-cohort monitoring with launch-gate discipline.** Engagement, attrition, crisis-screening rates, warm-handoff completion, citation-coverage, companion-pattern-violation, and outcome metrics vary by language, channel, condition, age cohort, sex, and social-determinant flags. Per-cohort dashboards reviewed by behavioral-health clinical leadership, operations, compliance, and patient-experience teams.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2037[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2038[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome-correlation pipeline as multi-quarter to multi-year post-launch commitment.** The pipeline pulls subsequent encounter records, screening-instrument trajectories, hospitalization rates, treatment adherence, and (with appropriate caution) attempted-suicide rates. Mental-health outcome attribution is harder than chronic-disease attribution; the analysis is suggestive rather than causal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2039[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2040[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-language deployment with validated translations.** Per-language asset development includes validated therapeutic-content translations, validated psychoeducation translations, validated regulatory-disclaimer translations, validated crisis-screening-instrument translations, per-language tone calibration, and per-language equity monitoring.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2041[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2042[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Eligibility check and off-ramp for excluded populations.** Patients with primary psychotic-spectrum diagnoses, patients in active inpatient or residential treatment, patients with primary substance-use disorders requiring specialized treatment, minors (in adult-only deployments), and others as defined by clinical leadership are routed to appropriate alternative care, not enrolled in the bot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2043[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2044[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Disaster-recovery topology with crisis-pathway resilience.** When the therapeutic-content store, the crisis classifier, the warm-handoff workforce queue, or any escalation pathway is unreachable, the bot degrades gracefully with direct routing to crisis resources. Per-source failover is documented and tested quarterly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2045[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2046[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Compensation operations for inappropriate responses.** When a patient or clinician disputes a bot response, the operations team reproduces the conversation, retrieves cited content, and either confirms the bot followed protocol or identifies the deviation and feeds the failure mode into the improvement loop.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2047[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2048[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy rigor.** Several mature commercial vendors offer mental-health support products. Most major institutions run a hybrid: build a thin orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for licensed therapeutic content and (sometimes) for the licensed-clinician workforce.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2049[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2050[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational ownership across multiple teams.** The bot sits at the intersection of behavioral-health clinical leadership, the licensed-clinician workforce, compliance, regulatory, IT, the call center, patient experience, the malpractice carrier, and (in some institutions) the equity and patient-advocacy office.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2051[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2052[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S1 (HIGH). Promote therapeutic-content-corpus-as-code lifecycle to architectural primitive. Specify per-content-item semantic versioning, sandbox testing against held-out support cases, staged rollout with per-content canary, rollback-on-regression, named ownership at the behavioral-health-clinical-leadership plus operations plus compliance plus regulatory team, per-content-version-stamping on every support-decision-record, annual review cadence, and behavioral-health-clinical-leadership signoff as launch gate. Extend to crisis-screening-classifier, FDA-strategy-artifact, consent-language, and mandatory-reporting-routing-policy as parallel versioned governance assets. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2053[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
